# **Introduction and Key Information** {#introduction-and-key-information}

This is high-key a complicated process if you have not modded games before or dug around in the innards of an Unreal game before. Make sure you have your caffeine on hand and an hour or two to throw at this to learn the ins and outs. I have tried to make this PDF as easy and beginner-friendly to follow along with as possible, but it is still complicated. However, once you do this process once or twice, you will get the hang of it.

Links for every tool I mention are located where I mention them and also at the bottom of this document.

Also, there will be multiple programs and files that you will need to download in order to follow this tutorial. Some of these will be downloaded from known websites, others from GitHub. If these things worry you, this is not the tutorial for you.

If you have trouble, feel free to DM me on discord, my username is LxSun

You can also join my personal/streaming discord and ask questions there: [https://discord.gg/KFRYQY7Gzt](https://discord.gg/KFRYQY7Gzt)

You can also ask questions in the Modding section of the main VEIN Discord.  
[https://discord.gg/vein-survival](https://discord.gg/vein-survival)

# **Downloads and Important Set-Up** {#downloads-and-important-set-up}

**You will need all of these programs in order to do the most basic of modding in VEIN:**

Get a program for unzipping and zipping files. I use 7Zip.  
[https://www.7-zip.org/download.html](https://www.7-zip.org/download.html)

Get FModel. I use the most recent version.  
[https://github.com/4sval/FModel/releases](https://github.com/4sval/FModel/releases)

Download the Mapping File from my drive.  
[https://drive.google.com/file/d/1V--pT6lnhp6Xx7D6Xvh8NSiwc1tqndav/view?usp=sharing](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1V--pT6lnhp6Xx7D6Xvh8NSiwc1tqndav/view?usp=sharing)

Get UAssetGUI  
[https://github.com/atenfyr/UAssetGUI/releases](https://github.com/atenfyr/UAssetGUI/releases)

Get UnrealPak  
[https://github.com/Dmgvol/UE\_Modding/raw/main/Tools/UnrealPak.zip](https://github.com/Dmgvol/UE_Modding/raw/main/Tools/UnrealPak.zip)

## **Setting Up FModel** {#setting-up-fmodel}

Step 1: Unzip and run the FModel.exe

- NOTE It may pop up saying that you need .NET 8.0 or later installed. It will take you to the webpage to get it, which is one of Microsoft's websites.

Step 2: Make sure “Detected Game” is **VEIN**

- If this is not available, click “Add Undetected Game”  
- Set Name: VEIN  
- Set Directory \- It should be something like:  
  - *C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Steam\\steamapps\\common\\Vein\\Vein\\Content\\Paks*

![][image2]

Step 4: Click OK.

Now FModel will load the game’s files, but we need to teach it how to read the files using the [mappings .usmap file that I linked above.](#downloads-and-important-set-up) 

Step 6: Click “Settings” in the top bar.  
	Under “General” enable “Local Mapping File”  
	Choose the Mapping File Path, this is where you put the Mapping that you got from my drive.  
	Choose your Output Directory. This is where any stuff you export from the game will be saved. Choose somewhere that you know.  
	Under “Models: Change Socket Format (ActorX) to “Don’t Export Bone Sockets”  
Click OK, FModel may need to restart.

Step 8: Once FModel is restarted, click “Archives” and then click “Load” \- This will load all of the files from the game and take you to the “Folders” tab.

![][image3]

## **Setting Up UAssetGUI** {#setting-up-uassetgui}

Step 1: Open UAssetGUI

Step 2: Click Utils \> Import mappings…

- Here, you will import the same .usmap file that you downloaded earlier and applied in FModel.

Step 3: Then in the top right of your screen, it should say “VEIN” and then you need to set the Unreal version of the game. 

- This is 5.4.

Step 4: Your UAssetGUI should look similar to this:

![][image4]

## **Setting Up UnrealPak** {#setting-up-unrealpak}

Step 1: Make a new folder in a location that you will be able to easily find.  
		I set up a folder called “VEINModding” for this.

Step 2: Unzip the UnrealPak.zip file that you downloaded into this folder.

Step 3: Make sure it looks like this:  
![][image5]

Step 4: You’re done\! That’s it. I know, super easy right? :P

# **Finding Stuff in FModel** {#finding-stuff-in-fmodel}

In FModel, you can poke around to find everything that exists within the game.

If you see a folder that has a “package” in it (as shown at the top of the screen under the folders tab) then you click on the “Packages” tab in order to see what is in it.  
You can then double click on the item in order to see the code, 3D Model, or whatever is included in that package.

Later, I intend on adding a quick guide here that will help you find commonly-used stuff within the game.

# **Mod Tutorial \- Changing and Adding Properties** {#mod-tutorial---changing-and-adding-properties}

## ***This tutorial walks you through editing properties on items and adding new properties on items.***

In this tutorial we will be recreating my [“Easy Lockpicking Mod”](https://www.nexusmods.com/vein/mods/6) in order to bring you through all of the steps necessary.

However, reading through it should give you a good idea on how to change values of things within the game without necessarily having to follow along step-by-step.

Step 1: Locate the locks within FModel.

- They are all located within Vein/Content/Vein/LockTypes

Step 2: Figure out where the lockpicking difficulty is kept.  
If you double click on LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple.uasset you won’t see anything related to that, so double click on the next one.

Step 3: We found the lockpicking difficulty modifier\! Great\! Now we can work on changing that. We should keep in mind that the “Simple” lock lacks this modifier though. That will be important later.  
![][image6]

Step 4: Locate all objects that will need adjusted.  
In our case this is every object that includes a “PickableEasinessModifier” AND additionally the BASE lock, which is the “LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple”

Our final list of exports is:

LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple  
LTD\_BasicLock\_Tough  
LTD\_BasicLock\_VeryTough  
LTD\_BasicLock  
LTD\_BasicLock\_CodeLock  
LTD\_BasicLock\_EnhancedLock  
LTD\_BasicLock\_RemoteLock

Step 5: Export these as Raw Data (.uasset)

This will export the data into the location that you determined earlier.

Once this is done, it will show have a link at the bottom of the screen that can take you directly to your exports.

Step 6: Open the first file in UAssetGUI

Open up [UAssetGUI](#downloads-and-important-set-up) which you downloaded and set up earlier.

![][image7]  
Next click File \> Open  
Navigate to your FModel Output folder.  
We will start with LTD\_BasicLock. Open that file.

Step 7: Find the property you are looking to change  
Remember\! We are searching for “PickableEasinessMultiplier” property and based on what we saw in FModel, it should be at 0.5 for this lock type.  
![][image8]

Step 8: Change that property.  
Double Click the “0.5” on the “PickableEasinessMultiplier” line and change it to “10”.

Step 9: Save your changes.  
![][image9]

Step 9.5: *\*\*Note\! When you edit a file in UAssetGUI, it will save a backup (\*.bak) file in the original directory. Feel free to delete these or keep them. It does not matter and won’t affect anything.\*\**

Step 10: Adjust all of the remaining lock types EXCEPT LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple since that does not have the “PickableEasinessMultiplier” property.

Step 11: Oh shit\! We’ve just realized we are going to need to ADD a property instead of just changing things\!

This is where things get difficult. This issue is because we need to ADD a property to an item in the game, rather than just CHANGE something.

Changing things is EASY. Adding things is COMPLEX.

Step 11.5: At this point, you are going to be editing code, but it isn’t terribly hard. You will just need a text editor that can handle JSON. 

- Notepad++ and VSCode are a couple of options, but it is up to you what you use.  
- I will be using Notepad++ for the sake of this tutorial.

Step 12: Saving the thing we WANT and the thing we HAVE  
We need to export a reference (the thing we want) and also the file we want to modify (the thing we have) as JSON.

1. Open LTD\_BasicLock\_VerySimple in UAssetGUI  
2. Click File \> Save As  
3. Name it LTD\_BasicLock\_VerySimple and set the “Save as type” to UAssetAPI JSON (\*.json)  
4. Open LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple in UAssetGUI  
5. Click File \> Save As  
6. Name it LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple and set the “Save as type” to to UAssetAPI JSON (\*.json)  
7. Navigate to the location that you saved these JSON files and open both of them.  
   1. In Notepad++, you can open one in each viewer, so you can see the documents side by side.  
8. On the VerySimple Lock, scroll until you see “PickableEasinessMultiplier” OR you can click ctrl+F to search the document for PickableEasinessMultiplier.  
   1. Make sure to take note of the surroundings. For this example, you’ll see the property before PickableEasinessMultiplier is “bRemovable” and the one after it is “RequirementsToCopyLock”. Keep this in mind\!  
9. On the Simple Lock, scroll until you see one of those surrounding properties, or ctrl+F to search for it. You will find that bRemovable is on line 182-190 and RequirementsToCopyLock is on line 191-234.  
   1. Due to how the other one is set up, we want to slot our change right in the middle of those two.  
10. On the VerySimple lock, copy the code related to Pickable Easiness.  
    1. Code we are copying:

               {

                 "$type": "UAssetAPI.PropertyTypes.Objects.DoublePropertyData, UAssetAPI",

                 "Value": 10.0,

                 "Name": "PickableEasinessMultiplier",

                 "ArrayIndex": 0,

                 "IsZero": false,

                 "PropertyTagFlags": "None",

                 "PropertyTagExtensions": "NoExtension"

               },

11. On the Simple lock, click on the }, on line 190, press enter, and paste that code.  
    1. Make SURE that it looks EXACTLY like the one before it and the one after it\! Do not miss ANY symbols, commas, or brackets, or it will NOT work.

![][image10]

12. Save the newly edited LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple.json  
13. Go back to UAssetGUI and open your newly edited LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple.json  
14. Ensure that it now contains the “PickableEasinessMultiplier” Property.

![][image11]

15. Success\! If everything loaded in correctly here and you can see the property, then you likely did everything right\!\~ Great job\!  
16. Click File \> Save As and overwrite the old LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple.uasset

![][image12]

17. Set up your mod folder hierarchy  
    1. Go back to the location that you’ve been saving everything.  
    2. Delete the .json files (LTD\_BasicLock\_VerySimple.json and LTD\_BasicLock\_Simple.json)  
       1. Optional: Delete the backup (.bak) files. This is not required but it will save some space in your mod.  
    3. Create a folder with the title of your mod  
       1. Mine will be “LxEZLockpicking\_P”  
       2. It MUST end in “\_P”  
       3. Open the folder. Now we will be copying the way the game sees the files (Just like the folder layout in FModel)  
       4. Create another folder inside called “Vein” and open it.  
       5. Create another folder inside called “Content” and open it.  
       6. Create another folder inside called “Vein” and open it.  
          1. Yes, “Vein” is there twice, just like in FModel.  
       7. Create another folder called “LockTypes” and open it.  
    4. Copy and paste ALL of your Lock files (the .uasset and the .uexp) into this folder. It should look something like this:

**The next step is on the next page because it will need pictures and I can’t fit more here :’)**

[**Make sure to add the Important Note to your mod if you upload it somewhere\!**](#important-note:)

## **Packing Files using UnrealPak** {#packing-files-using-unrealpak}

18. Move your mod folder (The one that ends in \_P to the folder where your UnrealPak is located.  
    1. Mine is called “VEINModding” as I explained in the [UnrealPak setup.](#setting-up-unrealpak)  
    2. Here is an example:

19. Drag your mod folder (the one ending in \_P) onto “UnrealPak-With-Compression”

    

    

    

    

    

20. It will pop up with a command prompt to show you the progress as it packs your mod into a .pak file.  
21. Press any key once it completes to finalize and it will close the command prompt.  
      
22. Now back in your folder, you’ll see that a .pak file has been created\!   
    1. Mine is called: LxEZLockpicking\_P.pak

Final step on the next page\!

23. Move your mod .pak file into the Paks folder of the game\!   
    1. It should be something like this:

    C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Steam\\steamapps\\common\\Vein\\Vein\\Content\\Paks

24. Load the game up and test it out\!

Note: There’s a weird thing with the lockpicking to where setting the multiplier to 10 makes it so that you unlock stuff by moving the pick ALL THE WAY to the right and pressing D to attempt the unlock, rather than being able to do it anywhere. I don’t know why this is, I’m assuming it’s just based on how the game is set up.

# **Setting Up An Unreal Engine Project** {#setting-up-an-unreal-engine-project}

Start by Installing Unreal Engine 5.4.4

I would provide steps for this, but I think you can figure it out.

When you start Unreal Engine 5.4.4, here is how to create a project for making mods for VEIN.

1. Start by launching Unreal Engine 5.4.4  
2. Select the GAMES category on the left  
3. Select “Blank”   
4. Set your project location to wherever you want that has a good amount of space.  
5. Make the Project Name: Vein  
6. Click Create

Ta-Da\! All done. Your project exists. Tutorials will use this in the future.

This is what you need for the most basic of mods made in Unreal Engine. Please look at the [Unreal Engine (Advanced) portion of this document](#unreal-engine-project-\(advanced\)) in order to continue setting up this project for more complex mods.

# **Mod Tutorial \- Changing Fonts in VEIN** {#mod-tutorial---changing-fonts-in-vein}

## ***This tutorial walks you through changing out the fonts used in VEIN.***

In this tutorial we will be recreating my [“Comic Sans Font Changer” Mod](https://www.nexusmods.com/vein/mods/11) in order to bring you through all of the steps necessary to replace fonts.

Changing fonts in VEIN is actually quite easy.

HOWEVER, you will need to install Unreal Engine 5.4.4 and have a base-level knowledge as to how to navigate it. [You will also need to have an Unreal Engine Project set up. Check here to make sure you do it right.](#setting-up-an-unreal-engine-project)

1. Open up your UE Project called Vein.  
   1. [If you need to set up the project, go here.](#setting-up-an-unreal-engine-project)  
2. Start by opening the content drawer. You should be in the “All” section of the content drawer.  
3. Create a new folder called “Vein” and open that folder.  
4. Create a new folder called “UI” and open that folder.  
5. Create a new folder called “Fonts” and open that folder.  
   1. It should look like it does below:

![][image13]

6. Drag your desired font into the content drawer within the Fonts folder.  
7. On the “Font Face Import Options” pop-up  
   1. Check “Apply to All”  
   2. Click “No”

![][image14]

8. You should now see your font in the content drawer

Next step is tedious but quick.

9. You need to copy (ctrl+C) and paste (ctrl+V) that font and rename it.  
   1. You will end up with 8 copies of it.  
10. Time to rename all 8 copies. Here are the names you need to give them:

    BebasKai

    FF\_Inter

    FF\_Inter-Bold

    FF\_Inter-ExtraBold

    FF\_Inter-ExtraLight

    FF\_Inter-Light

    Title

    US101

![][image15]

[**Make sure to add the Important Note to your mod if you upload it somewhere\!**](#important-note:)

11. Now you need to “Cook” these fonts.  
    1. Click “Platforms” in the top of your screen  
    2. Then click “Windows”  
    3. Then click “Cook Content”  
    4. AT THIS POINT if you get a pop-up saying you’re missing something, ignore tf out of that. Just proceed anyway and tell it not to pop up again lol.

12. Find your COOKED content.  
    1. Go to your Unreal Engine Project folder  
    2. UnrealEngine Projects \> Vein \> Saved \> Cooked \> Windows \> Vein \> Content \> Vein \> UI \> Fonts  
13. Great\! You found it. Each font should have a .uasset .uexp and a .ufont file for it.  
    1. Double check that each of these are there.

NEXT PAGE PLS

14. Make a mod folder.  
    1. I’m going to name mine LxComicSans\_P  
       1. It MUST have “\_P” at the end of it.  
    2. Open that mod folder  
    3. Make a new folder called “Vein” and open it.  
    4. Make a new folder called “Content” and open it.  
    5. Make a new folder called “Vein” and open it.  
       1. Yes, Vein is twice. Get used to this lol.  
    6. Make a new folder called “UI” and open it.  
    7. Make a new folder called “Fonts” and open it.  
    8. Move all of your newly cooked files into this folder. It should look something like this: 

![][image16]

15. Move your mod folder (The one that ends in \_P to the folder where your UnrealPak is located.  
    1. Mine is called “VEINModding” as I explained in the [UnrealPak setup.](#setting-up-unrealpak)

16. Drag your mod folder (the one ending in \_P) onto “UnrealPak-With-Compression”  
      
17. It will pop up with a command prompt to show you the progress as it packs your mod into a .pak file.  
18. Press any key once it completes to finalize and it will close the command prompt.  
19. Now back in your folder, you’ll see that a .pak file has been created\!   
    1. Mine is called: LxComicSans\_P.pak  
20. Move your mod .pak file into the Paks folder of the game\!   
    1. It should be something like this:

    C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Steam\\steamapps\\common\\Vein\\Vein\\Content\\Paks

21. Load the game up and test it out\!

# **Unreal Engine Project (Advanced)** {#unreal-engine-project-(advanced)}

This tutorial will be for setting up Unreal Engine to handle the basics of Logic Mods or Blueprint Mods.

Important: [You need to set up UE4SS in order for mods that need this advanced setup to work.](#downloading-and-installing-ue4ss-for-mod-devs)

1. Make sure your project name is “Vein”  
   1. *“But I already did this\!”* Nope\! You just think you did, so follow along.  
   2. Click Edit \> Project Settings  
   3. Where it says “Project Name” it is likely currently blank  
      1. \*\*shocked pikachu face\*\*  
   4. Put “Vein” here.

![][image17]

2. Disable Io Store and enable Chunk Generation  
   1. Click Edit \> Project Settings  
   2. On the left, under “Project” find “Packaging”  
   3. Find “Use Io Store” and disable it.  
   4. In the same location (Project Settings \> Project \> Packaging) find “Generate Chunks” and turn that on.  
3. Enable Chunk ID Assignments  
   1. Click Edit \> Editor Preferences  
   2. On the left, under “General” find “Experimental”  
   3. Now find the “User Interface” dropdown and enable “Allow ChunkID Assignments”

These few changes will let you package .pak logic mods and blueprint mods from within Unreal Engine without having to use UnrealPak (which can sometimes have issues with these types of mods).

# **Downloading and Installing UE4SS for Mod Devs** {#downloading-and-installing-ue4ss-for-mod-devs}

You have to have UE4SS to load logic mods and blueprint mods.  
[https://github.com/UE4SS-RE/RE-UE4SS/releases/tag/experimental-latest](https://github.com/UE4SS-RE/RE-UE4SS/releases/tag/experimental-latest)

**Version You Need: zDEV-UE4SS\_v3.0.1-599-g1a6cdbc**

UE4SS adds an extreme level of functionality to your mods, however **these mods will now also require the end user (the player) to also install UE4SS in the same version.**

When you upload your mod, make sure to set UE4SS as a requirement with a link to either [my prepackaged UE4SS for VEIN mod](https://www.nexusmods.com/vein/mods/15) and/or the github link.

1. Scroll all the way down on the Github page, and click on **zDEV-UE4SS\_v3.0.1-599-g1a6cdbc** to download it.  
2. Go to your Steam Library, find "VEIN", right click, click "Manage"\>"Browse Local Files".  
- From here on out, this will be called your \<GAME\_ROOT\> folder.

  Example: "C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Steam\\steamapps\\common\\Vein"

3. Navigate to the following folder: 

   \<GAME\_ROOT\>\\Vein\\Binaries\\Win64\\

4. Extract the zipped folder "UE4SS-VEIN" into the Win64 folder.  
- If you've done everything correctly, the Win64 folder should now contain the following:


  D3D12			|	File Folder

  DML﻿﻿﻿﻿  			|	File Folder

  Ue4ss			|	File Folder

  dwmapi.dll﻿   		|﻿	Application extension

  tbb.dll﻿﻿﻿ 			|﻿	Application extension

  tbb.pdb﻿﻿  			﻿|﻿	PDB file

  Tbbmalloc.dll		|	Application extension

  Tbbmalloc.pdb﻿﻿		|	PDB file

  Vein-Win64-Test﻿  		|	Application

  Vein-Win64-Test.pdb  	|﻿	PDB file


5. Verify that both the ue4ss folder and the dwmapi.dll are both in the same folder as "Vein-Win64-Test.exe"  
6. Open the game once and close it in order for UE4SS to add itself to your install.  
7. You should now have a new folder called "LogicMods" in the following location:  
   "\<GAME\_ROOT\>\\Vein\\Content\\Paks"  
8. This “LogicMods” folder will be the location where you put logic mods and blueprint mods that you make.

# **Mod Tutorial \- Blueprint Modding: Making a Simple Widget** {#mod-tutorial---blueprint-modding:-making-a-simple-widget}

First, make sure that you have followed the [Unreal Engine Project (Advanced) section](#unreal-engine-project-\(advanced\)) AND [downloaded and installed the Dev version of UE4SS v3.0.1-599-g1a6cdbc.](#downloading-and-installing-ue4ss-for-mod-devs)  
If you do not do both of these, your mod **will not work**.

This Mod Tutorial is a test to make sure that both UE4SS and Unreal are set up correctly to be able to make and run Logic and Blueprint mods.

1. In Unreal, navigate to your Content folder and make a new folder called “Mods”.  
2. Within that folder, make a new folder, this will be the name of your Test Mod.  
   1. I will call mine “TestMod”.  
3. Open the TestMod folder (or whatever you named it).  
4. Create the ModActor.  
   1. Right click, under “Create Basic Asset”, click “Blueprint Class”.  
   2. Click “Actor”.  
   3. Rename it to “ModActor”.  
   4. Leave it be for now, we will come back to it.

5. Click File \> Save All  
   1. Get used to saving often.

6. Create a Widget Blueprint  
   1. Right click again, under “Create Advanced Asset”, click “UI”, and “Widget Blueprint”.  
   2. Click “User Widget”.  
   3. Rename your Widget, make it start with “WBP\_” as this is standard and will help later.  
      1. I will call mine “WBP\_TestWidget”.

   

7. Your folder should now look similar to this:

![][image18]

8. Familiarize yourself with the Blueprint Editor  
   1. Double click on the new widget blueprint (WBP\_TestWidget if you’re following along) to open it up.  
   2. On this screen, there’s the “Palette” on the top left, this is where different options for your widget are located.   
   3. Below that, on the left, is the “Hierarchy”, this is where everything you add to your widget is kept.  
   4. The center of your screen is the viewport. This is where you will see anything you add to your widget in real time.  
   5. The right side of your screen, which is currently blank, is the “Details” section. This is where you will make edits to anything you add to your widget.  
9. Customize your Widget Blueprint  
   1. On the Palette Search bar, search for “Canvas Panel”.  
   2. Drag this onto your widget in the Hierarchy (WBP\_TextWidget).  
      1. There should now be a roughly 16:9 rectangle in your viewer.  
   3. On the Palette Search bar, search for “Text”.  
   4. Drag this onto your widget in the Hierarchy.  
      1. There should now be white text in your viewer that says “Text Block”  
   5. Click on the Text item in the hierarchy, or on the viewer.  
      1. I find that it’s easier to click on the hierarchy than on the viewer, personally as you might accidentally click the Canvas or something else instead if you use the viewport, but it’s up to you.  
   6. In the details panel, find “Content” and “Text”  
   7. Change the Text to anything you want.  
      1. I will change mine to “Mods working\! Huzzah\!”  
   8. Because of how VEIN is, you should move the text to the center of the screen instead of the top left.  
      1. On the main screen, there’s some UI that will block the top left, which will make it hard to see.  
   9. You can move the text in two ways\!  
      1. Using the Details panel (Slot \> Position X & Position Y).  
      2. Using the Viewport panel (Clicking and dragging your text).  
   10. Feel free to customize your text in whatever ways you wish.  
       1. I am going to make mine size 64\.  
   11. Once you’re done with the text, click “Compile” in the top left and then file \> save all

![][image19]

10. Familiarize yourself with the Event Graph  
    1. Open the Content Drawer and double click on the ModActor Blueprint Class  
       1. This should all look familiar to you, however we won’t be using this part.  
    2. In the Viewport, at the top, click “Event Graph”  
       1. The main portion of your screen is now showing the Event Graph. This is where you will be writing code via blueprints.  
       2. The top left is the components within the scene. Don’t worry about this for now.  
       3. The bottom left is where you can add functions, variables, and more. Don’t worry about this either for now.  
       4. The right side is, again, the details section where you can make specific changes to this actor. Don’t worry about this for now xD.  
    3. There are three sections in the Event Graph itself  
       1. Event BeginPlay  
          1. This is things that will happen right when the actor is started (or the game is started in our case)  
       2. Event ActorBeginOverlap  
          1. This is something that will happen when this actor overlaps another actor, for example, a player walks into a trigger.  
       3. Event Tick  
          1. This is not recommended to be used outside of UI, as it’s something that will update EVERY game tick or even more often.   
          2. Don’t use this in your mods much unless you want to cause severe FPS drops.

11. Tell your ModActor to show the widget in game  
    1. On the Event Graph, locate “Event BeginPlay”  
    2. Drag from the arrow and let go in empty space.  
    3. Type “Construct” and click “Construct object from class”  
    4. Click the dropdown under “Class” and type in your widget name.  
    5. Drag from the arrow on Construct \<your widget name\> and type “Add to Viewport”

*\*\*Note from Sun: if there are spelling errors from here on out, it’s because my cat has decided to lay on my mouse and smack his tail on my keyboard. I will try to fix them later lmao.\*\**

6. Drag from the “Return Value” blue dot on Construct \<your widget name\> and connect it to the “Target” blue dot on “Add to Viewport”  
   7. Click Compile and then File \> Save All

![][image20]

12. We now need to assign our mod to a chunk.  
    1. Open the Content Drawer  
    2. Highlight the ModActor and your widget (Shift+Click works)  
    3. Right click on one of them and click Asset Actions \> Assign to Chunk  
    4. Choose a number that you will remember, and always have your mods use different numbers from one another to make life easy.  
       1. I am going to use 42  
    5. File \> Save All

13. *It’s time to cook, Jesse.* We are now going to compile our project.  
    1. Click back to your Untitled Scene tab at the top of your screen.  
    2. Click the “Platforms” dropdown at the top of your screen.  
    3. Click Windows \> Package Project  
    4. Choose a packing location.  
       1. I use my “UnrealEngine Projects\\Vein” folder.  
    5. It will take 30 seconds or so to package the project.

14. Locate your Packed .Pak  
    1. Go to the folder you selected  
       1. For me this is UnrealEngine Projects\\Vein”  
    2. From there, go to Windows\>Vein\>Content\>Paks  
    3. Find your pakchunk  
       1. It will be named pakchunk(NUMBER YOU CHOSE)-Windows.pak  
       2. Mine is pakchunk42-Windows.pak  
    4. If you see also pakchunk\<YourNumber\>-Windows.ucas and/or pakchunk\<YourNumber\>-Windows.utoc then you need to go back to the [Unreal Engine Project (Advanced) section](#unreal-engine-project-\(advanced\)) and make sure you didn’t skip any steps.   
       1. Your mod will not work.  
    5. Rename it to your mod name (from the folder in unreal engine on step 2). **It must match exactly**.  
       1. My mod name is TestMod so I’m renaming mine to TestMod.pak  
    6. Keep this file explorer window open on this Paks folder. You will need to copy/move your mod to another location in the next steps.

Next Page pls\!

15. Locate your LogicMods folder.  
    1. It will be located at \<GAME\_ROOT\>\\Vein\\Content\\Paks  
       1. To open the Game Root, go to your Steam Library, find "VEIN", right click, click "Manage"\>"Browse Local Files", this is your Game Root folder.  
    2. Open the LogicMods folder.  
16. Copy/Move your mod .pak to the LogicMods folder.  
17. Start the game and see if the text pops up on the main menu screen.

![][image21]

18. If that worked then…

**Congrats\! You just made your first blueprint mod for VEIN.**   
**You can now add an extremely large amount of things and functionality to the game.**

# **Stuff for the future\!** {#stuff-for-the-future!}

If you want to export models and stuff from FModel, it’s very similar to what we did before, you will just click “Save model” instead of “Export Raw Data”

If you want to import those models into Blender for viewing or editing, you will need the io\_scene\_psk\_psa which is the psk/psa importer plugin for Blender.  
[https://github.com/DarklightGames/io\_scene\_psk\_psa](https://github.com/DarklightGames/io_scene_psk_psa)

You can use any version of blender. But if you’re using Blender 4.2 or higher, you can download the PSK/PSA importer plugin from the Blender Extensions platform built within Blender, if you’re using an older version (4.1 or lower) then you need to use a different version of PSK/PSA importer. See more info here: [https://github.com/DarklightGames/io\_scene\_psk\_psa?tab=readme-ov-file\#legacy-compatibility](https://github.com/DarklightGames/io_scene_psk_psa?tab=readme-ov-file#legacy-compatibility)

That’s most of my knowledge at this time. 

A great resource if you’re looking for more stuff (some of it doesn’t work or doesn’t work THE SAME) then there’s a great series of tutorials at this github link: [https://github.com/Dmgvol/UE\_Modding](https://github.com/Dmgvol/UE_Modding)  
Keep in mind that some of the wording can be a bit confusing and it did take me a couple of hours to figure out the “adding properties” situation. 

I also am unfamiliar with Unreal Engine, so that’s part of the issue for sure lol.

# **Important Note:** {#important-note:}

**This is serious\! We do not want to burden the Devs with extra work\!**

If you upload your mods ANYWHERE, make sure to include this disclaimer:

**\*\*\*IMPORTANT NOTE\!\!\!\*\*\***  
**If you experience ANY bugs or glitches while you have this mod, or any others, installed, please make sure to remove the mods and test if the bug continues before reporting it to the devs\!\!\!**

You know how people are, and we don’t want to cause bugs and glitches through modding that the devs then have to spend their time solving, only to find out it was because we missed a comma in our code.
